  "answer": "**Ghalib's maqta (closing couplet with takhallus):**\n\nExamples from *Diwan-e-Ghalib* illustrate the maqta as the final *sher* (couplet) incorporating the poet's pen name \"Ghalib,\" often with self-referential wit or irony, a hallmark of Urdu ghazal convention.[^1][^2][^3]\n\n- Ghazal 1:  \n  *Tu ne qasam mai-kashi ki khaayi hai Ghalib  \n  Teri qasam ka kuch aitbaar nahin hai*  \n  \"You've sworn an oath, O Ghalib, to give up the wine,  \n  But in your vow, the faith of any prayer is not there.\"[^4]\n\n- Ghazal 26:  \n  *Kuch toh padhiye ke log kehte hain  \n  Aaj 'Ghalib' ghazal-sara na hua*  \n  \"\\\"Do speak some verse,\\\" the people have begun to say,  \n  \\\"For Ghalib has not sung a single ghazal today.\\\"\"[^5]\n\n- Ghazal 195 (explicitly labels couplet as \"Maqta\"):  \n  *Liye jaati hai kahin ek tavaqqo Ghalib  \n  Jaada-e_rah kashish_kaaf_karam hai hum ko*[^6]\n\n**Persian maqta:** No Persian ghazals or divans are in the Falsafa corpus (37 works total, focused on translated philosophy/classics; literature is mostly Urdu here, plus Old English). No examples available.\n\n**Urdu vs. Persian divergences:** The corpus contains Urdu ghazal collections (*Diwan-e-Ghalib*, *Diwan-e-Zauq*) but no comparative poetics, treatises (e.g., no Urdu/Persian *'ilm al-ghazal*), or explicit discussion of takhallus placement (typically penultimate/final in both, but Urdu often more playful/self-mocking), closing turn (maqta), or rhetorical posture. Searches for \"maqta,\" \"takhallus,\" \"ghazal\" yield verse examples only, no analysis. This topic isn't covered; the corpus lacks relevant Persian/Urdu theory texts.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/01-aa-ke-meri-jaan-ko-qarar-nahin-hai/translation/#p-4304e1).  \n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 26 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/26-dard-minnat-kash-e-dawa-na-hua/translation/#p-57b20e).  \n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 195 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/195-waan-pahunch-kar-jo-ghash-aata-paye-ham-hai-hum-ko/transliteration/#p-090051).  \n[^4]: *Ibid.*, ch. 1.  \n[^5]: *Ibid.*, ch. 26.  \n[^6]: *Ibid.*, ch. 195.",
